Is this type overly complicated ? could not the same be expressed in a simpler way ? export type Timings = Record<
	string,
	Array<
		{ desc?: string } & (
			| { time: number; start?: never }
			| { time?: never; start: number }
		)
	>
>;

This type can be simplified depending on your exact needs. Let's break down what this type currently represents:

1. It's a Record (key-value object) with string keys
2. The values are arrays of objects that:
   - Optionally have a `desc` property
   - Must have either a `time` property OR a `start` property, but not both

Here are some simpler alternatives:

```typescript
// Option 1: If you don't need the mutual exclusivity of time/start
export type Timings = Record<string, Array<{
  desc?: string;
  time?: number;
  start?: number;
}>>

// Option 2: If you really need the mutual exclusivity
export type TimingEntry = {
  desc?: string;
  time?: number;
  start?: number;
} & (
  { time: number } | { start: number }
);

export type Timings = Record<string, TimingEntry[]>;
```

However, if you absolutely need to ensure that `time` and `start` are mutually exclusive (meaning an object can have one or the other but never both), then your original type is actually a good way to express this constraint. In that case, you might just want to break it into smaller parts for readability:

```typescript
type TimingEntry = { desc?: string } & (
  | { time: number; start?: never }
  | { time?: never; start: number }
);

export type Timings = Record<string, TimingEntry[]>;
```

Choose the version that best matches your requirements for type safety vs. simplicity.
